Problems Faced & How I Solved Them
1. curl -H "Host: ..." failed the TLS handshake (filter_chain_not_found, connection reset)
Envoy's HTTPS listener routes by SNI (set during the TLS handshake itself), not by the HTTP Host header (sent after TLS is already established). Connecting to https://localhost:18443 sent SNI localhost, which matched nothing. Fixed by using curl's --resolve host:port:ip flag instead, which makes curl use the real hostname for both SNI and cert verification while still connecting to 127.0.0.1.
2. kubectl: command not found after previously working fine
Bash had cached a stale binary path (/usr/local/bin/kubectl) that no longer existed, even though kubectl was correctly installed via snap (/snap/bin/kubectl, present in $PATH). Fixed with hash -r to clear bash's command cache and force re-resolution from $PATH.
3. curl: (77) error setting certificate file
The /tmp/imesh-ca.crt file referenced by --cacert didn't exist in the new shell session (opened a fresh WSL terminal partway through). Re-ran the kubectl get secret ... | base64 -d > /tmp/imesh-ca.crt extraction command to regenerate it before retrying.
